{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170963/1937123001/0721.xml":{"full_text":"NATIONAL NEWS\nYULE TRAGEDIES\nOF MANY KINDS\nTAKE 231 LIVES\nFive Burned to Death as Oil\nHeater Explodes Six\nDrown as Car Plunges\nInto Creek\n[By the Associated Press, Dec. 26]\nViolent death shackled tragedy\nonto the Christmas scene of scores\nof families across the nation today.\nWith more than 231 reported\nkilled, the toll mounted hourly\u2014\nfatal crashes on streets and high\nways, sfiootirigs,'train wrecks; and\nflaming death in the night came to\nfive members of a family gathering\nat Auburn, Me., when an oil heater\nexploded and destroyed a cottage.\nTwo of the victims, trapped as they\nslept, were little girls.\nKilled When Hit by Train\nSix men drowned in a creek when\ntheir automobile ran off the road near\nWellsburg, W. Va.\nSheriff Herbert Trauhert identified\nthe men from papers found on the\nbodies as:\nThomas Whitfield. Samuel Ross an 1\nThomas Vaskn, all of Houston, Pa.;\nDonald Everett and John Kurkoski.\nboth of Midland, Pa.: and Howard\nCodol of Canonsburg, Pa.\nFrosted windshields cost the lives\nof three persons in a head-on auto\ncrash at Fort Dodge, la., and a rail\nroad crossing collision near Danville,\n111., resulted in sudden death to Fied\nCarter. 51,. Gates (Ind.,) coal mine\noperator, whose car was hit by a\nWabash railroad freight train.\nIllinois reported 25 Yuletide deaths,\nPennsylvania IS, California 15, Ohio 1\n16 and Maryland 14.\nA collision between a 10-car mall\nand express train and nn 11-car pas\nsenger train at Hopkinsville, Ky\u201e\ncaused injuries to 25 persons.\nChild of Three Killed\nSanta Claus meant death to Jimmie.\nMaloney, aged three, in Lancaster. S.\nC. Toddling across a street, to dis\nplay his Christmas gifts to neighbors,\nhe was struck down by a car and\ninstantly killed.\nIn Winchester, Va.. James Corbin.\n14, met violent death when struck\ndown as he rode on a shiny new bi\ncycle he had just received for Christ\nmas.\nTn Weston. Mo., a quarrel around\nthe family Christmas tree ended in\nswift tragedy when a man killed his\nbrother's wife and then committed\nsuicide.\nChicago had a similar Incident. Po\nlice said Thomas Burns. 32. shot and\nkilled his father, James Burns. 65.\nwhen his father became angry \u201cfor\nnothing at all.\u201d The father was found\ndying on a chair beside an undec\norated Christmas tree.\nIn Indianapolis, a woman making\nlast-minute Christmas purchases\u2014her\narms full of gay-wrapped boxes\u2014died\nunder the wheels of a street car.\nIn New York, a hit-run motorist,\nafter killing a pedestrian, attempted\nto run down a policeman in making\nhis escape. The driver swung his car\nat the patrolman and sped away amid\ngun-fire from the officer's revolver.\nHours later, the pedestrian victim was\nidentified by his son-in-law in the\nmorgue.\nAt Pittsburg, the two sons of Will\niam Strous, a railroad fireman,\nwaited anxiously for their father to\narrive home from his run for Christ\nmas dinner. He never came. He was\nkilled in a wreck a mile .from the\nstation.\nIn Kentucky, a crippled boy shot\nhis father fatally; in Alabama, a cm\nvict took his own life by poison; and\nin Arizona, a homeless hobo fell to\ndeath from a boxcar.\nViolent deaths by states Included:\nAlabama 7. Arizona 3. Arkansas 5.\nCalifornia 15, Connecticut 8. District\nof Columbia 3. Florida 7, Georgia 4,\nIllinois 25, Indiana 2, lowa 3. Kansas\n3. Kentucky 6, Louisiana 5, Maine 7.\nMaryland 14. Massachusetts 5, Michi\ngan 7, Mississippi 3. Missouri 7. New\nJersev 2, New York 5, North Carolina\n3, Ohio 16. Oklahoma 2, Oregon 3.\nPennsylvania 18. Rhode Island 2.\nSouth Carolina 6, Tennessee 5. Texas\n6, Utah 2. Virginia 5. Washington 8,\nWest Virginia 6, Wisconsin 3.\nCONGRESS TO FACE\nNEW DEMANDS FOR\nFINISHED PROGRAM\nRoosevelt Said Determined\nto Force Showdown On\nAims of New Deal\nWashington. Dec. 23 Undismayed\nby the fruitless special session of\nCongress, President Roosevelt has de\ntermined to lay before the January\nsession demands for completion of his\nnew deal program. Democratic leaders\ndisclosed today.\nShowdowns that may be reflected\nin the 1938 congressional elections are\nto be forced on tho administration's\nbudget balancing, wage-hour, anti\nmonopoly, farm relief, national de\nfense, foreign policy, tax and social\nplanning legislation.\nMr Roosevelt told his congressional\nchleftnlns he would remain in Wash\nington until miti-Fet.ruaiyi to present\nhis program. He plans to give a gen\neral outline of his plans to Congress\nIn a personally-delivered message at\nthe opening of Congress. January 3.\nand will submit special messages ask\ning for specific legislation from time\nto time.\nBouhts Future Congress\nDescribed as having his \u201cchin set.\u201d\nthe President was said to believe that\nunless his program is acted on at the\ncoming session hy the overwhelming\nDemocratic Congress elected with him\ntn 1986. there would he less oppor\ntunity to get action on reform legisla\ntion In *ho new Congress to be elected\ntwo years before his second term Is\ncompleted.\nParty leaders also reported that Mr\nRoosevelt was demanding budget\nbalancing economy with a view to\ntransferring some funds from high\nway aid. the CCC nnd national youth\nadministration, to build up a bigger\narmy nnd navy In view of the Inter\nnational situation. They pointed out\nthat an armament building plan would\ngive as much employment as outlays\nfor roads and the CCC.\nThe executive wns represented as\ndetermined to put the full respon\nsibility on Congress If It appropriates\nrelief funds In excess of the budget\nestimates he will submit, because. It\nwas said, If this country is forced\nBroadcast by President\nSets Note for Christmas\nRoosevelt Retells Heywood Broun Story Promising\n'Peace to Poor Iscariot\u2019\u2014Trade Reports Better\u2014\nNation\u2019s Needy Feted\n[By the Associated Press]\nA Christinas eve address by Presi\ndent Roosevelt, broadcast from Wash\nington. set a spiritual note for the\nnation as It celebrated the beginning\nof a holiday week that was ushered\nin with reports of material business\ncheer.\nThe President repeated a story\nwritten by Heywood Broun, a news\npaper columnist, which ended with\nan admonition that \"peace on earth\nmeans peace to Pilate, peace to_ the\nthieves ii me mw. and peaie io'pool\nJsea-not\nThe marts and shops were' closed\nfor the holiday, cash registers ring\ning up purchases which approached\nlast year\u2019s record sum for six years.\nA survey of the New York metro\npolitan area indicated the trend. It\nshowed a total only seven-tenths of\n1 per cent under the 1936 figure.\nAir lines and railroads reported\ntraffic had been heavy.\nA four-generation reunion filled the\nWhite House, but for the second year\nin a row the President\u2019s wife was\nabsent, visiting her daughter in Seat\ntle, Mrs Anna Boettiger, who has\nbeen ill.\nMrs James Roosevelt, daughter-in\nlaw of the President, took over duties\nas the White House mistress.\nLast year, the President\u2019s wife\npassed Christmas at the bedside of\nher son. Franklin, Jr., who was re\ncuperating in Boston from a sinus\noperation.\nVice-President John Garner planned\n\"a day of quiet and rest\" in his\nWashington hotel, his wife said, while\nTreasury Secretary Henry Morgen\ni thau joined his family in Fishkill.\nN. Y\u201e and Post inaster-General James\nI A. Farley and Labor Secretary Fran-\nI cos Perkins joined their families in\nNew York city.\nGiving to the Needy\nOrganizations of all sizes and types\nmade the season one of generous\ngiving to the needy, with the Salva\ntion Army, the Red Cross and settle\nment houses and relief organizations\nas active as any time in recent years.\nAbout 800 indigent youngsters\nI joined the navy in Christmas feasts\non Uncle Sam\u2019s warships at San\nPedro, Cal. Each received a $4 or $5\npresent.\nOne of the largest Christmas\ndinners planned for the poor was one\nof chicken fricasse and trimmings\nfor 10,000 itinerants at New York\ncity\u2019s municipal lodging house. A\n\"hobo college\" dedication early Christ\nmas morning was arranged with an\nother party for New York homeless.\nThe Children's Ai<h society of the na\ntion's metropolis was giving dinners\nand presents to 30.000 youngsters.\nEven the animals were not forgot\nten as 500 Boy Scouts in New York\nmade their annual trip to the parks\nto feed the birds and harnesses,\nblankets and other gifts were hand\ned out at the. humane society head\nquarters to 900 dogs, 200 cats and one\nhorse.\nCaroling on a Mountain\nCapt William H. Wincapaw. New\nEngland's \u201cSanta Claus of the air,\"\nmade his ninth annual airplane trip\nto drop Christmas packages to lonely\nlighthouse keepers on the northeast\ncoast. Similar flights were made in\nAlaska, and Hawaii broadcast greet\nings to mid-Pacific islands which have\nbecome important American aviation\nbases.\nThe custom in southern states of\nushering the holMny in with a dis\ncharge of firecrackers persisted, al\nthough manj- cities prohibited their\nuse. Atlanta for the first time.\nAnother unique custom for this na\ntion continued in the Pennsylvania\nsections where descendants of Ger-\nman forbears greeted Bclsnickle -not\nSanta Claus. Kris Kringle or St Nick.\nHe brought toys for good youngsters\nand a switch for had ones.\nAt Hot Springs national park. Ar- i\nkansas. last night, about 290 singers I\nof carols filed down a mountainside\nto a huge natural ampithcater\u2014the j\nsite where the late Senator Robinson I\nwas notified in 1928 of his nomina- i\ntion tor the vice-presidency. Scores\nof living Christmas trees and the\nwooded promenade were ablaze with\nlights.\nFrom Santa Claus, Ind., a Christ\nmas greeting was sent to all children I\nof the nation who have had infantile\nparalysis. The message went to Keith I\nMorgan, chairman of the President's\nbirthday committee for aid of the\nsufferers, from 12-year-old Norman\nPhillips, son of the postmaster. It j\nwas an annual message from a boy\nwho once had the disease and whose\nfather receives thousands of chil-\ndren's letters addressed to Santa Claus\nevery year.\ninto war. a balanced budget would be\nimperative in order to finance a con\nflict.\nSupport from Dies\nFrom an unexpected quarter today,\nthe President received support for his\nbudget-balancing drive from Repre\nsentative Martin Dies (D.. Tex.) who\nled the successful fight against the\nadministration's wage-hour bill in the\nspecial session.\nIn a letter to Mr Roosevelt, the\nTexan said a \"conference or caucus\"\nof at least 100 conservative nnd south\nern Democrats would be called early\nin January to pledge support to the\nexecutive's economy plan as stated\nvesterdav in a letter to Representative\nCartwright (D.. Okla.) urging a SIOO,-\n000,000 slash in highway funds.\nAssailing \"so-called liberals,\" and\ntheir spending proposals. Dies wrote\nMr Roosevelt.:\n\"Your definite nnd courageous posi\ntion on this (economy) subject will\ndetermine once and for all who are\nliberals and who are spendthrifts.\nSome members have confu\u201c I the vast\n..ft\".:\nThey think that extravagance is syn\nonymous with liberalism when, as a\nmatter of fact, the very essence of\nliberalism Is sound money and sound\ncredit.\u201d\nDies warned that many members\nwant to economize on all other hut\ntheir own constituencies, and unless\nthe economy nx was generally applied\nthe job of cutting down spending\nwould be difficult. He predicted that\n\u2022'so-called liberals will oppose every\neffort you make to balance the budget\nand will clamor for bigger appropria\ntions tn he distributed among their\nconstituents, without proposing mens\nures to increase the federal income.\"\nDies added he was confident the\nconservative Democrats would vote to\nincrease revenues to balance the\nbudget.\n(Copyright. 1937. I. N. S.l\nTOWN WITHOUT WATER\nWHEN BIG MAIN BURSTS\nProctor, Vt.. Dec. 29 \u2014(AP)\u2014A big\nwater main burst tonight nnd left\nthis village of 2500 without Its reg\nular water supply for two hours.\nFiremen strung hose to a temporary\nsource which officials snld would pro\nvide enough water until repairs to\nthe main were made.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN; SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, DECEMBER 30, 1937\n\u20193B WILL SEE TEST\nOF UNEMPLOYMENT\nINSURANCE SETUP\n\nOn January 1 the Balance\nof This. Tremendou& Sav\nings Account Will Be\nAbout $400,000,000\nWashington. Dec. 25\u2014On January\n1, 1938, some 12 million working men\nand women in America will be pos\nsessed of a joint savings account, in\nthe United States treasury, with a\nbalance approaching 3400.000.090.\nThey may not, of course, present\nthemselves on the day following to\ndemand that their share in this joint\naccount be pushed through a cashier\u2019s\nwindow. For this joint account is an\ninsurance fund, a reserve which the\ngovernment hopes will cushion the\ntragedy of individual unemployment\nas it may occur in the coming\nmonths and years.\nA major part of the omnibus so\ncial security law enacted in the sum\nmer of 1935. the unemployment com\npensation program will receive its\ncrucial test during the coming year.\nFor two full years, longer in the case\nof Wisconsin, employers of 23 states\nhave been contributing to this joint\naccount for their employes. In six\nof these states, employes themselves\nhave added regular deposits. In one\ninstance that of the District of Co\nlumbia, the,\u201cstate\" also has made a\ncontribution to the balance now on\nhand.\nThe results of this program of taxa\ntion in the 23 states, about to begin\nbenefit payments, are shown in the\naccompanying table.\nUnited\nStates\ntreasury\nEm ployes credit\nState covered on Nov. 1\nAlabama 277,000 $7,261,385\nArizona 70.000 1,622,188\nCalifornia 1,216,000 54,547,197\nConnecticut. 408,000 12,683,940\nD. of Columbia 131,000 4,980,102\nLouisiana 214,000 5.928,353\nMaine 132.000 3.025,174\nMaryland 295,900 6,548,988\nMassachusetts 851,000 31,416,870\nMinnesota 395,000 7,767,399\nNew Hampshire 93,000 3.636,488\nNew York 2.616.000 88,572,078\nNorth Carolina 370,000 7.822.323\nOregon 146.000 5,051,004\nPennsylvania 2,401.090 56,095,952\nRhode Island 169.000 6.794,822\nTennessee 296,000 6,547,677\nTexas 708.000 16.073.744\nUtah 68.800 2.111.955\nVermont 44,000 1,129,216\nVirginia 316,000 6,203,347\nWest Virginia 316,000 7,669.557\nTotals $11,565,000 J 340.489.768\nWisconsin 111,000 28,300.000\n(In the case of Wisconsin, its pro\ngram was enacted before the federal\nlaw and some benefits were paid in\n1936 and 1937. It is now becoming\npart of the federal-state system in\nall particulars.)\nDuring this two-year period of\nsteady contributions, nn withdrawals\nhave been permitted; by law, none\ncould be made until sufficient funds\nhad been accumulated to meet the\nestimated maximum demands. With\nthe country currently in a new eco\nnomic tailspin and unemployment\nmounting at an alarming rate, benefit\npayments now are becoming permiss\nible in the states listed.\nNeedless to say, the demand for\nsuch payments will be scrutinized\nsomewhat anxiously by those con\ncerned with the question of whether\nthis part of the social security pro\ngram Ls going to pay for itself. With\ncomparable interest, it will be scru\ntinized also by those administering\npublic unemployment relief, since an\nimportant argument advanced for the\ncompensation program was that it\nwould tend to level off this unpre\ndictable but recurring burden.\nBy and large, it was estimated by\nthose who devised the unemployment\ncompensation program that the pro\nceeds of a 3 per cent pay roll tax\nin the eligible occupations would or\ndinarily balance each year the de\nmands for unemployment benefits.\nWith this in mind, the tax rate is be\ning raised gradually from 1 per cent\nin 1936, to 2 per cent in 1937 and 3\nper cent in 19?^.\nWBZA IS ORDERED\nTO BAR EVE JOKES\nNew York. Dec. 23 (AP) \u2014Word\nwent out from the National Broad\ncasting company today to keep the\nname of Mae West out of all pro\ngrams over which it has control.\nIssued privately to 16 stations in 12\ncities, the order was designed to fore\nstall any joking references that might\nbe made to the widely discussed\n\"Adam and Eve\" sketch broadcast\nfrom Hollywood the 12th.\nAlthough not. made public, it was\nunderstood the interstation commu\nnique said In effect: \"Plense watch\nscripts for mention of Mae West\u2019s\nname and keep It out.\"\nAn exception probably would he\nm V- Jo the event Miss West figured\nin a news broadcast.\nThe sketch, In w Inch the buxom ac\ntress made one of her infrequent radio\nappearances, aroused a storm of crith\nclsm. particularly from religious\ngroups, and provoked talk In Congress\nof tighter radio regulations.\nPublic apologies were Issued by\nPresident Lenox R. Lohr of N.8.C.,\nby the coffee company which spon\nsored the program, and by the s|x>n\nsor's advertising agents, to anyone\nwho might have taken offense nt the\nfervor with which Miss West read her\nlines,\n\"It was a mistake,\" the advertising\nagents snld. \"and wo can assure the\npublic at large that the same mistake\nwill not be made again.\"\nToday's action by N.B.C. apparently\nwas taken as a double chock against\nnny repetition of the Incident.\nEfforts to reach Miss West nt her\nHollywood apartment brought the\nstatement from a friend that she\n\"Isn\u2019t speaking to anyone about that.\"\nN.B.C. officials recalled that they\nhad taken similar precautions nguinst\nquips aimut the duke of Windsor fol\nlowing his abdication, but they could\nnot remember ever having banned\nthe name of u movie actress before.\nStations covered by the company\u2019s\norder Include WBZ. Boston, and\nWBZA, Springfield, Mass.\nPROJECTS MUST\nBE KEPT DOWN,\nPRESIDENT SAYS\nRoosevelt Calls On Con\ngressmen to Be Content\nWith Smaller Slices for\nTheir Areas\nWashington, Dec. 22 (AP)\nPresident Roosevelt called on mem\nbers of Congress today to be content\nwith smaller slices of federal funds\nfor their pet projects, in order that\nthe budget may be approximately\nbalanced.\nAfter reciting what he termed\n\"unpalatable\u201d but \u201cperfectly true\u201d\nfacts about the necessity for\neconomy, he said in a letter to Rep\nresentative Cartwright (D., Oki.):\nWould Mean \u2018\u2022lnsolvency\u201d\n\"More than 3000 counties in the\nUnited States are glad to get every\npossible expenditure of federal funds\nwithin their counties, but I know you\nwill agree with me that if we legis\nlated with that as the principal ob\njective in mind, there would not be\nany Democratic party and there would\nnot be any solvent government after\na few years.\u201d\n\"The Congress,\u201d the chief executive\nsaid, \"has a perfect right constitution\nally to exceed the budget, but. if the\nbudget is exceeded, obviously the Con\ngress must accept, full responsibility,\nand obviously the Democratic luili\nbers, which have such a large majori\nty in the Congress, must equally ac\ncept the full responsibility.\u201d\nThe letter dealt with road building\neconomies\u2014a subject on which Con\ngress so far has failed to follow the\nPresident\u2019s recommendations. Recent\nly, Mr Roosevelt suggested curtailing\nthe road construction program by\ncanceling certain authorizations be\nfore January 1.\nFailure of Congress to repeal the\nauthorizations at the special session\nleft rhe secretary of agriculture no\nalternative to.apportioning among the\nstates $214,000,900 for use on roads\nin the next fiscal year.\nCartwright, chairman of the House\nroads committee, wrote the President\nrecently that no member of his com\nmittee has requested a meeting for\nimmediate consideration of cancela\ntion.\nHe said he personally did not favor\n\"a proposal to cancel all authoriza\ntions for roads for the next fiscal\nyear, and to single out roads for a\ndrastic and arbitrary reduction in sev\neral subsequent years, especially when\nno assurance has been given that cor\nresponding reductions in other activi\nties will be recommended.\"\nMaking \u201cHonest Effort\u201d\nIn reply, Mr Roosevelt said the ad\nministration, by lopping off nonessen\ntial appropriations, \"is making an\nhonest effort to cut the budget down\nto a figure which will closely approx\nimate the estimated tax receipts.\"\nDeclaring he must eliminate pro\nposed expenditures which provide the\nleast work and favor those which give\nthe most, the President asserted that\n\u201cmoney spent on federal aid highways\ntakes very few people directly off the\nrelief rolls.\u201d\nHis letter recognized, however, the\ndifficulties in the path of road cur\ntailments. Speaking as a former mem\nber of the New York Legislature, he\nsaid he appreciated the \u201cpulling and\nhauling when it comes to getting a\nslice of the government\u2019s expenditures\nfor one\u2019s own projects.\u201d\nIf he had all the money in the\nworld to spend, he said, he would\n\u201cgladly go ahead with road building\nin every county\u201d on an \u201ceven greater\nscale.\u201d\nWashington. Dec. 22 \u2014(AP) \u2014A new\nadministration hid for enactment of\nwage and hour legislation came to\nday from Secretary Wallace. The\nagriculture department chief expressed\nhope that representatives from farm\nareas would support the sidetracked\nlabor standards bill at the regular ses\nsion of Congress beginning in January.\nHe told reporters that the bill was\nnecessary to promote a \u201cmore con\nstructive balance\u201d between labor and\nagriculture.\nMay Give Personal Message\nSenator Barkley of Kentucky, the\nDemocratic leader, predicted after a\nvisit at the White House that the\nPresident would deliver that message\nin person. Word already had spread\nabout the capital, following a confer\nence between Mr Roosevelt and a\ngroup of liberal Senate supporters,\nthat he would re-state administration\nobjectives and contend the current\nbusiness recession was largely psy\nchological.\nRecession Test Welcomed\nFor Nunn-Bush Labor Plan\nMilwaukee, Dec. 25\u2014(AP) \u2014Henry\nL. Nunn says he expects the current\nbusiness recession to prove his nn\nnual-income-for-labor plan is good\neconomics.\nMoreover, he hopes to show that\nInstead of high wage rates, labor\nneeds steady work and a good in\ncome each year. He hopes to demon\nstrate that the way to beat hard\ntimes is to produce goods at prices\nthe consumer can pay.\nNunn, president of the Nunn-Bush\nShoe company, said continued suc\ncessful operation of his company's\nplan guaranteeing its 700 employes\n52 weekly pay checks a year would\nbe the proof.\nBriefly the principles ami elements\nof the Nunn-Bush plan are these:\nThe enmnnnv considers its labor\na business partner, along with capital\nand management, it admits lalmr is\nentitled to a fair share of values it\nicreates- and pays it.\nThis is done through a group\nsalary; fund into which goes the\nwoikins' fixed percentage of gross\nshex\" sales receipts. Each employe is\nclassified as to ability and impor\ntance of his task. The next year\u2019s\nbusiness is estimated from past aver\nages. The Individual's share of this\nIs split Into 52 parts. The company\nthen pays him one fifty-second every\nweek. Finally, upward or downwar I\nadjustment of these drawing ac\ncounts is made every three or four\nmonths to compensate for differences\nbetween actual receipts and esti\nmates.\nSince July S. 1935. Nunn-Bush fac\ntory bands have received a check\nwhether they worked a full week,\ntwo days nr not nt all. Their annual\nIncome was considerably higher than\nthe Industry's average.\nBut now there has been n reces\nsion. Is the Nunn-Bush plan work\nable In a period of decline? Some\nindustrialists say \"no.\" Nunn believes\nIts real value will be disclosed.\n\u201cNow that we have taken out\nlabor into a partnership,\" Nunn said\nin an Interview, \"we are no longci\ntied to high wage contracts. We\ndon\u2019t have to shut down to await a\n\u2018THUGS\u2019SAID HIRED\nTO BEAT UNION MEN\nAT AUTO FACTORIES\nLabor Board Alleges Com\npany Influenced Workers\nat Homes \u2014Martin Sees\n\u2018Lesson\u2019 for Ford\nWashington, Dec. 23\u2014(AP) \u2014The\nNational Labor Relations board, de\nciding today that the Ford Motor\ncompany violated the Wagner labor\ndisputes act, declared that the con\ncern showed \u201cunconcealed hostility\u201d\nto unionization.\nThis antagonism, the board said,\nwas brought home to workers\n\u201cthrough the employment of hired\nthugs to terrorize and beat union\nmembers\u201d and through other acts of\n\u201ccoercion.\u201d\nTold to Reinstate Men\nThe board ordered the company to\nreinstate 29 employes who. the deci\ni sion said, were discharged for union\n[activity in violation of the Wagner\nact. The company was directed to\nstop discouraging membership in the\nUnited Automobile Workers or any\nother union.\nThe Ford company immediately\nchallenged the decision. A company\nstatement issued at Detroit said it\nwas \u201cbased on prejudice\u201d and that an\nappeal would be taken to the United\nStates circuit court of appeals.\nHomer Martin. U.A.W.A. president,\nsaid. \u201cThe decision should teach Ford\nthe never-to-he-forgotten lesson that\nthe vast industrial empire he so auto\ncratically controls must adapt itself\nto the inevitable development of mod\nern industry\u2014namely, the emergence\nand permanence of labor unions.\u201d\nOne Complaint Dismissed\nThe decision resulted from com\nplaints by the U. A. W.. which is a\nC. I. O. union. A U. A. W. complaint\nthat the company had discharged six\nother employes for union activity was\ndismissed, however.\n\u201cFrom the mass of testimony in\nthis proceeding, two facts stand out:\nThe unconcealed hostility with which\nthe Ford Motor company views bona\nfide labor organizations and the utter\nruthlessness with which it has fought\nthe organization of its employes,\u201d the\nboard said.\n\u201cThe respondent (the Ford com\npany), not only through public inter\nviews and statements, but through\nthe direct circulation of antiunion lit\nerature within its plants, has made\nits antagonism to labor organizations\nso evident that no employe whose eco\nnomic life is at its mercy can fail to\ncomprehend it.\n\u201cHired Thugs** Employed\n\"The full significance of this antag\nonism has been brought home to its\nemployes through the constant hos\ntility of foreign and supervisory offi\ncials, through the systematic dis\ncharge of union advocates, through\nthe employment of hired thugs to ter\nrorize and beat union members and\nsympathizers, and through numerous\nother acts of intimidation and coer\ncion recited above (in the testimony).\n\u201cThe chief weapon of the respond\nent in this fight to prevent self\ni organization among its employes has\ni been the Ford service department..\n\u201cThe record leaves no doubt that\nthe service department has been\nvested with the responsibility of main\ntaining surveillance over Ford em\nployes. not only during their work,\nbut even when they are outside the\nplant, and of crushing at its incep\ntion. by force if necessary, any sign\nof union activity.\n\u201cThus within the respondent\u2019s vast\nRiver Rouge plant at Dearborn the\nfreedom nf self-organization guaran\nteed by the act has been replaced by\na rule of terror and repression.\n\u201cDummy Organization**\n\u201cEvidently fearful that the forego\ning measures might not suffice to re\nstrain the growth of the U. A. W., the\nrespondent fostered a 'dummy\u2019 labor\norganization of its own choice\u2014the\nFord Brotherhood of America, inc.\nWe find that the respondent has dom\ninated and interfered with tha forma\ntion and administration of this organ\nization and has contributed to the\nsupport of it.\u201d\nEighteen of the 46 closely-typewrit-\nten pages in the board\u2019s decision were\ndevoted to a description of the trouble\nat two River Rouge plant gates last i\nMay 26.\nThe board called \u201calmost unbeliev-\nably brutal\u201d the story of attacks on\nunion officials and handbill distribu-\ntors as developed at a hearing on the\nunion's complaint.\nmore favorable labor market. The\nchief concern of stockholders, man\nagement and workers alike is profit\nable production at prices the con\nsumer will pay.\n\u201cUnderstand, the workers will not\ncarry tho full load. As raw materials\nbecome cheaper, we can reduce shoe\nprices. We also can maka additional\nprice cuts, since we do not have to\nconsider hour or piece wage rates.\nWe shall maintain or Increase our\naverage volume. That means steadv\nwork and nn assured Income.\n\"Since our labor receives a pre\ndetermined part of the receipts, the\nmore it produces, the more it earns.\"\nNot Paternalistic\nNunn said the plan wns neither\nphilanthropic nor paternalistic and\ncould 1^ made to operate in industry\ngenerally. He addeu that capital Hist\nmust recognise labor wot a c0.'..-\nmodify: management must abolish\ndictatorial policies; and labor must\nlearn to differentiate between wago\nrates and annunl Income.\n\"Mon today want nnd expect to\nhave some say about the conditions\nunder which they work.\" Nunn said,\nexplaining how he put his theories\ninto operation. \u201cAs soon as our firm\nprogressed to tho point where the\nfactory manager could no longer\npersonally maintain contact with the\nIndividual, the management Invited\nthe workeis to organize.\n\"Now. a new employe selected by\nmanagement must bo accepted by\nhis fellow workers Any discharge\nmust bo approved by the workers.\nAll wages, working hours, rules of\nnil kinds must be mutually agreed\nupon before nny changes can be\nmade. Resort to outside arbitration\nwas provided In ease of failure to\nagree.\n\"We Inaugurated that policy 85\nyears ago. What seemed to lie a sur\nrender by management of Its rightful\npower proved to be a gain of power.\nIn an atmosphere where there wa.i\nno arbitrary \u2018boss\u2019 dictation, no\nhatred or prejudice wns possible We\nwork together without fear or suspi\ncion of each other.\u201d-\nFrom this start toward owner-\nNavy Rebuilding May Be Big\nIssue in Regular Session\n\nAny Administration Plans /or New Construction May\nStimulate Support of Ludlow War-Referendum,\nCapital Observers Feel\nU.S. CONTROL ASKED\nFOR AIR TRANSPORT\nBY INDUSTRY ITSELF\nUnique RceoHTmcndation\nMade in Annual Report of\nAviation Group\nChicago, Dec. 26\u2014In a move unique\nin the annals of American transporta\ntion, rhe nation's commercial airlines\ntonight asked for government control\nof their industry.\nRegulation of the airlines by a \"non\npolitical. competent, permanent agen\ncy of government\u201d was urged In the\nannual report of the Air Transport\nAssociation of America.\nThe report, released by Edgar A.\nGorrell, association president, also\nrecommended:\n1. Establishment of a system of\ncertificates of convenience and neces\nsity similar to that now in effect for\nrailroads and public utilities.\n2. Cooperative action among the\nairlines to eliminate waste, to promote\ninterline travel and to avoid oppres\nsive measures, under direction of the\nregulatory body.\n3. Government control of all new\nfinancing for Commercial airlines.\n4. Banning of' cons'di-latinns. mer\ngers and interlocking interests except\nas specifically approved by the pro\nposed regulatory agency.\nAccording to Col Gorrell, an agency\nof the haracter proposed would com\npare with the Interstate Commerce\ncommission, which not only regulates\nrailroad rates and schedules, but con\ntrols financing and corporate struc\ntures of the carriers.\nThe National Maritime commission\nlikewise exercises a similar control\nover American shipping.\nAt present, federal control of avia\ntion is confined to the bureau of air\ncommerce, which regulates actual\nflight operations and safety measures,\nand the postoffice department, whit*\nregulates schedules on air mail con\ntract lines.\nDuring 1937 the airlines, according\nto Col Gorrell, experienced their ban\nner year, hut still suffered an aggre\ngate operating loss of $3,000,000. This\nloss, he said, is attributable to money\nspent for safety aids, increased labor\ncosts, higher material prices and rigid\nadherence to high operational and\nmaintenance standards.\nReferring to the need for certifi\ncates of convenience and necessity.\nCol Gorrell said they would eliminate\nunsound and unjustified measures and\nprevent piratical practices. Competi\ntion could be preserved and smaller\nlines protected.\nFORD PLANS FIGHT\nON NLRB ORDER TO\nSUPREME COURT\nWill Reply On I Oth Day to\nBoard\u2019s Edict That It Rein\nstate 27 \u2014\u2018Phooey\u2019 Says\nBennett to Martin\nDetroit, Dec. 24\u2014 (APl\u2014The Ford\nMotor company spurned overtures\nfrom the United Automobile Work\ners of America today and drafted a\nlegal campaign to resist a National\nLabor Relations board order that it\ncease antiunion activities.\nA company spokesman said the\ncase would be carried to the United\nStates supreme court, if necessary.\nThe board allowed 10 days for com\npliance with its order. A representa\ntive of the Ford company said there\nwould be no announcement on pro\ncedure until January 3. That would\nbe the 10th day after the board is\nsued its decision in Washington that\nthe company had violated the Wag\nner labor relations act. a decision\nthe company said was \u201cbased on\nprejudice.\u201d\nmanager worker partnership. the\ncompany came to the annual income\nplan.\n\u201cA look at the statistics showed\nfactory pay rolls since 1921 have\nbeen practically the same as total\nfarm income.\u201d Nunn said. \"Now.\nwhen wage rates go up. prices rise.\nEventually. the consumer rebels.\nBusiness falls off. Factories close\nWorkers become idle. Their Income\nceases.\n\"It seemed apparent labor docs not\nunderstand these truths, so we set\nabout making them evident by giving\nour workers a guaranteed percentage\nof the value of all merchandise the;\nproduced.\n\u201cWe believe that given such an\nagreed percentage, lalxtr generally ne\nit has in our organization, will per\nceive the immutable law that, to\nhave more, one must produce more\n\"Thus, labor will become sympa\nthetic to the problems of manage\nment since it will be seen that they\nare identical with labor s own prob\nlems. Wage rates will cease to lie a\nbone of contention since it will be\nperoMvcd that income mcrensis not\n\u2666.ith rates, but with efflrdoory\nand the volume of goods produced.\"\nNunn said the plan, from the com\npany's viewpoint, had resulted in:\nA loyal, cooperative, self-respecting\nlabor group; negligible labor turn\nover; freedom from labor troubles\ngreater efficiency; reductions of\nwaste, since each worker realizes a\ntwitched job costs him money: flexi\nbility of production costs permitting\nspeeidy adjustment to market condi\ntions.\nRepresentative workers said in\neffect:\u2014\n\"Fifty-two pay cheeks a year give\nus a feeling of Independence and\nsecurity; a planned future that will\ninclude some of the better things in\nlife.\"\nAnd Henri I- Nunn?\nThis friendly, mild.mannered trans\nplanted southerner said ho was\nhappy man. confident of his com\npany's future\nNear the desk In his modestly\nfurnished factory office stands a\nthree-foot loving cup. gift of his em\nployes and constant reminder of the\nesteem in which they hold him\n\"Maybe It was the crusader in me\nthat started this.\" Nunn said \"but\nI'm sure were on the right track.\nAnd do you know, my life ns a man\nager now is one grand, sweet songl\"\nBy KIKKE I- SIMPSON\nWashington, Dec. 25 \u2014(AP) \u2014Events\nare shaping to put \u201cbig navy\u201d advo-\ncates, both in and out of Congress,\nin a position they have not known\nsince the .nd of the World war. Indi-\nm rebuilding will\nbe a major item of debate in the\nregular session of Congress.\nAdministration reluctance to dis-\n..-I Si plum may.\nbe contemplating tor new naval cou-\n'\"C' 1 ,n R\ndebate of the matter would arouse\npeace organizations to new activity.\nIt might stimulate support of the\nLudlow war-referendum resolution,\nvigorously opposed by President\nRoosevelt.\nThe naval construction question\nprobably will come up as a move to\nmeet the business recession. The\nidea behind it Is to divert relief out\nlays to an undisclosed extent from\nother work-relief projects to naval\nconstruction either of combat or aux\niliary craft because that course would\ngive lagging heavy industry and un\nemployment a quick recovery stim\nulus.\nPresident Roosevelt\u2019s letter to\n(\u2019hairman Cartw'right of the House\nroads committee over congressional\nopposition to reducing highway ap\npropriations in an effort to approach\na budget balance is significant. It\ndeals with job making relativity.\u201d\n\u201cIf I have to get the budget down\nto a certain figure. obviously, I must\neliminate the proposed expenditures\nwhich provide the least work and\nfavor those expenditures which give!\nthe most work.\" the President said.\nNaval and other ship building, one\ngroup argues, falls within this rule.\nAlready congressional committees are\ndiscussing with Maritime commission\nofficials plans for an oil tanker con-\nstruction program involving from 1\nto 20 vessels. The navyt also has urged I\nexpediting the authorized two-battle- i\nship replacement program and the\nadding of two additional ships. Re\ncent presidential conferences with high i\nnaval officers are described as involv\ning construction plans.\nPossible Diplomatic Angle\nThe aspect of any proposal to give\nimpetus to navy building which will\n1 not be stressed is the diplomatic ef\nfect it might have abroad. Yet that\nangle is certainly uppermost in the\nminds of navy building advocates.\nSpeeding up fleet reconstruction and\nI projecting the possibility of future\nnaval expansion, these advocates con\ntend, would go far to strengthen\nAmerican peace influence and pres\ntice abroad, particularly in the Far\nEastern situation.\nShort of new and grave incidents\nm China, dispatch of additional Amer-\nScan warcraft to the Far East for\ndemonstration or any other purpose\nis improbable. Whatever Great Brit\nain finally does about reinforcing her\nfar eastern fleet, Washington policy\nj gives no intimation of parallel\nj American action.\nAnnouncement of a formidable\nI long-range program of battle fleet re\nconstruction would probably have\nI greater effect in Japan than any ac\ntual parade or warcraft. It would put\nI Japan on notice, at least, that her\nactivities in China were tending to\npush the Washington government into\nI the new world naval armament race\nlon a scale that might alter naval\nratios in the Pacific.\nGreat Britain is feverishly engaged\nin fleet expansion to meet, primarily,\nthe problems raised for her by Ger\nman and Italian policies. The rising\ntide of naval construction talk in\nj Washington points toward a similar\ncourse by this country.\nSome far-seeing statesmen, how\never, hope that beyond these days of I\nbig armament will come a new era j\n'of peaceful adjustment of interna-1\nI tional disputes when the world effort\nwill be to scale armaments down in\nstead of up.\nAn American naval building pro\ngram of stupendous size operated in\n1921-22. That was followed by the 1\nnow scrapped naval limitation treaty\ns hat ended the sea armaments race\nl for a period of years. Some observers\nl^elieve the same result might be at-\ntained in the end by American re-\nentry into the naval race.\nCUMMINGS CLEARS\nDEMOCRATS IN SALE\nOF CAMPAIGN BOOK\nSays Prosecution Not War\nranted in Reply to Charges\nMade by Snell\u2014Will Ask\nLaw Be Amended\nWashington. Dec. 23 Atty-Gen\nHomer Cummings. in a letter made\npublic today, cleared Democratic na\ntion u.officials of Republican charges\nlof violating the corrupt practices act\nin selling 51.006.000 of campaign sou\nvenir hooks to corporations.\nAt the same time Cummings bared\nbis intention to recommend changes\nI in the corrupt practices act to Con\ng-css.\nRepresentative Snell of New Yorn.\nI Republican House leader, who demand\ned that Cummings make the investi\ngation. made public the letter without\ncomment. It was dated November 20\nCummings, informing Snell that he\n-I\u2019roscentlvn Not Warranted\"\n\"A comptehcnsiie study of the law\nand the facts has now been completed,\nand the conclusion has been reached\nthat a criminal prosecution would not\nbe warranted.\n\"The case is unlike that involving\nthe Narragansett Racing association\nWilliam Shawcross, chairman of the\nDemocratic committee of the state of\nRhode islaiiu. id James V Kennedy,\nformer chairman of the Democratic\nstate committee of Rhode Island, in\nwhich the government sought and se\ncured an indictment.\n\"My study of the general subject\nleads me to the conclusion that It is\ndesirable to amend the statute, with\na view to broadening Its scope nnd I\nrendering It more effective In Impo.\u2019-.\ntnnt particulars. To this end. I shall.\nIn the near future, submit to Congress!\nproposed amendatory legislation.\"\nSnell's charges. which had been laid\nbefore Cummings, involved Post-!\nmaster-General James A. Farley,\nchairman of the Democratic national\ncommittee, and other officials.\nHe submitted what punswted to ba I\na photoatatic copy of a letter signed\nbv M. H. Porter for the Democratic\ncommittee, urging corporations to:\npurchase the campaign book auto- j\ngraphed by President RooMValt.\n7\nNATIONAL NEWS\nINDEMNITY TOTAL\nFOR SUNKEN PANAY\nTO BE SET LATER\nJapanese Note Called \u2018Re\ni sponsive\u2019 in Reply by Sec\nretary of State\nWashington, Dec. 25 (AP)\nThe United States accepted today\n\u2022Japan's guarantees \u201cagainst in- j\nfringement of, or unwarranted in-\nterference with, the rights and\ninterests of the United States\u201d in\nChina.\nPansy Incident. which threat, jr\ny... M\ntwo countries, was considered closed\njas to its general lines. Some tech-\nnical points, chiefly the amount of\nthe indemnification, remain to be\nworked out.\nJap Note \u201cRe*pon\u00ablve\u201d\nSecretary Hull, in a formal \u2019\u2019\u2022W\nso the Japanese note of esterdajS\u00df\nsaid:\n\u2022The government of the Unitea\nStates regards the Japanese govern- 3\nment's account, as set. forth in the\nJapanese government s note of De-\nI cember 24, of action taken by it, as\nresponsive to the request made by\nthe government of the United States\nin this governments note of De\ncember 14.\u201d\nSecretary Hull conferred with\nPresident Roosevelt, Undersecretary\nSumner Welles and Assistant Secre-\ntary Hugh Wilson before inditing\nhis reply.\nThe United States continues to re\nly, however, on \u2019he facts contained\nin the findings of the navy court nt\ninquiry. This may be taken to mean\nthat this government does not admit\nthe version of \"mistake.\u201d as con\ntained in the Japanese note, but does\nnot intend to pursue the argument\nfurther.\n\u201cThe Earnest Hope\"\nAfter accepting Japan\u2019s note, Hull\nsaid in his reply:\n\"It is the earnest hope of the gov\nernment of the United States that\n\u2019he steps which the Japanese govern\nment has taken will prove effective\ntoward preventing any further at\ntacks upon or unlawful interference\nI by Japanese authorities or '\"rcee\nwith American nationals, interest*\nor property in China.\u201d\nThe United States note, of seven\nparagraphs, consisted chiefly of ref-c;\nerences to the American note of the\n14th and the Japanese notes of the\n14th and 24th.\nIt \u201cobserved with satisfaction the\npromptness with which the Japanese\ngovernment in its note of Decembers\n14 admitted responsrMlity. expressed X\nregret and offered amends.\u201d\nHull, who soon after the receipt of\n\u2019he Japanese reply of yesterday con\nsidered it satisfactory as to guarani^\n-ees (having already regarded as\nsatisfactory the note of the 14th with\nrespect to apologies and indemnified^\nI tions). took less than one day in\nwhich to reply.\nThe Gnsrantees\nWhat Hull accepted as guarantee\u00ae\nwas the following:\nI\u2014That1 \u2014That \"rigid orders\u201d were issued\nto Japanese military, naval and\nforeign office officials to ofeerve\nnore strictly repeated instruction^; J\nigainst infringement of United\nStates rights arid interests tn China.\n2\u2014That the Japanese government\nis \"studying carefully every nossiblO\nmeans of achieving more effectively\nthe above stated aims.\u201d\n3\u2014That the Japanese government\n\u201cis ascertaining, in closer contact\nwith American authorities in China,\nthe whereabouts of American inter\nests and nationals,\" presumably so\nas avoid unwarrantably interfer\ning with them.\n4\u2014That the Japanese government\nis improving means of communicat\ning intelligence with regard to the\nwhereabouts of American nationals\nand interests in China to the Jap\nanese authorities on the spot.\nJapanese sources here said the\nquestion of indemnifications would\nbe speedily settled by Japan\u2019s ac\ncepting any figure set by the United\nStates. The Japanese note said that\ngovernment \"wil! make IndemnifiU\ncations for all the losses.\"\nSources close to the state depart\nment summed up Hull\u2019s note as an\nacceptance with two implied reser\nvations:\u2014\nI\u2014That \u201cthe government of the\nUnited States relies on the report\nof findings of the court of inquiry\nof the United Stateu navy, a copy\nof which has been communicated of\nficially to the Japanese government\"\n\u2014(circumstances which may be in\nterpreted as disproving the Japan\neses contention of \u201cmistake.\")\n2 \u2014The United States wiU wait to\nsee how effective will be the Jap\nanese steps toward preventing inter\nference with Americans and Ameri\ncan interests.\nChronology of Panay\nAffair Is Recalled\nWashington, Dec. 25\u2014 (AP) \u2014Tht\nPanay incident, which, in It# general\nlines, was closed today by Secretary\nHull\u2019s note to Japan, began;\nSunday, December 12; The gunboat\nPanay was sunk by Japanese air\nbombs which abo sank or caused tn\ni>c beached three Socony Vacuum\ncompany umkeis on the Yangtzs\nriver above Nanking. Five men were\nkilled, nearly three score injured.\nThe incident continued;\nMonday. Dscsmber 13. Verbal apo\u00ab\no^ies of Japanese arrived througk\nEmbassador Grew in Tok io and Em-\nbassador Saito here.\nTuesday, December II; Japan apol\nogized profoundly in a formal notSb\nassumed ful responsibility,\nUl<l lUut'UilllGtdUUU, ,1. 'll I kOVA*\nment of officers responsible, and pro\nferred guarantee agumst future such\nincidents. The United States pre*\nseated Japan with a formal note of\nprotest, demanding full apologies, in\ndemnification and guarantees, not\nonly against repetition of such Inci\ndents but also against nil interference\nwith American nationals, interests or\npn\u00bbperties in China.\nMonday. December 20: Secretary\nHull wrote Senator Smathera (D H\nN. J.) that the United Stales soom\ntime ago had intended to withdraw\nits boats and military from China\nbut would not do so now.\nTuesday, December 21: President\nRoosevelt exchanged telegrams with\nhis 1936 opponent. ex-Gov London,\nin which he hinted the United\nStates might take the \u2018leadership\u2019*\nn what Hdidon called an \"extremely 7\nlelicute foreign situation.\u201d\nFriday. December 21; Navy de\npart ment publisbc<i official reports of\nComdr Hughes of the Panay and the\nnaval board of inquiry, finding that\nJavanese planes bombed the Panay\nfrom low altitude*, later machine\ngunned the Panay. Japan guaron\nteed there would bo no further inter\nteience with American rights and UM\nreieats m China,","height":"25785","width":"19935"}}
